  :prose
"Chapter 2 built cloth from springs. This appendix is the tuning
reference. The three sliders are stiffness `k`, rest length `L`, and
damping `b`. Combinations of these give you rope, hair, fabric, jelly,
rubber, chain, whip. All from the same `world/link!` primitive.

---

## F.1 The tuning axes

**Stiffness `k`** — how hard the spring resists being stretched. Low
`k` is a stretchy rubber band; high `k` is a rigid rod. In Motoi's
sim units, `k` in `[0, 1]`:
- 0.05 : very stretchy
- 0.20 : elastic (jelly)
- 0.40 : cloth-like
- 0.70 : firm (rope)
- 0.95 : near-rigid (rod)

**Rest length `L`** — the equilibrium distance between endpoints.
This is the length the spring 'wants' to be. In pixels.

**Damping `b`** — how much the spring bleeds energy per oscillation.
Low `b` rings for a long time; high `b` never oscillates.
- 0.001 : elastic energy preserved for many bounces
- 0.02  : gentle decay (rope, fabric)
- 0.10  : quick settle (hair, chain)
- 0.30  : heavily damped (thick putty)

---

## F.2 Preset table

| Material         | k     | b     | Notes                                         |
|------------------|------:|------:|-----------------------------------------------|
| Elastic band     | 0.15  | 0.010 | Very stretchy, rings when released            |
| Thin rubber      | 0.25  | 0.030 | Stretches noticeably, moderate damping        |
| Cotton thread    | 0.40  | 0.040 | Cloth-typical; slight stretch, quick damping  |
| Denim fabric     | 0.55  | 0.060 | Stiffer cloth, low stretch                    |
| Leather strap    | 0.70  | 0.100 | Firm, doesn't ring                            |
| Rope             | 0.65  | 0.080 | Firm but slightly springy                     |
| Chain link       | 0.85  | 0.120 | Rigid, very quick damping                     |
| Steel rod        | 0.95  | 0.150 | Effectively rigid; use for skeletons          |
| Hair strand      | 0.30  | 0.060 | Springy with body                             |
| Muscle fiber     | 0.50  | 0.100 | Firm but damped                               |
| Rubber band, hot | 0.20  | 0.005 | Rings audibly on release                      |

## F.3 Rope

```scheme
(define (rope-segment n rest-length)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (let ((balls (make-vector n)))
    (let loop-i ((i 0))
      (when (< i n)
        (let ((b (world/spawn 'rope (+ 100 (* i 2)) (+ 20 (* i rest-length)))))
          (entity/mass! b 0.5)
          (entity/drag! b 0.01)
          (when (= i 0) (entity/pin! b))
          (vector-set! balls i b))
        (loop-i (+ i 1))))
    (let loop-j ((j 0))
      (when (< j (- n 1))
        (let ((L (world/link! (vector-ref balls j)
                              (vector-ref balls (+ j 1)))))
          (world/link-rest!      L rest-length)
          (world/link-stiffness! L 0.65)     ;; rope preset
          (world/link-damping!   L 0.08))
        (loop-j (+ j 1))))
    balls))

(rope-segment 15 8)
```

15-segment rope, hangs, swings naturally.

## F.4 Cloth

```scheme
;; A 15x15 cloth grid, cotton-thread tuned.
(define (cotton-cloth cols rows spacing)
  (let ((g (cloth cols rows spacing)))
    (world/each 'thread
      (lambda (b)
        (world/each-link-of b
          (lambda (L)
            (world/link-stiffness! L 0.40)
            (world/link-damping!   L 0.04)))))
    g))
```

Cotton is soft and drapes. Denim is stiffer:

```scheme
(define (denim-cloth cols rows spacing)
  (let ((g (cloth cols rows spacing)))
    (world/each 'thread
      (lambda (b)
        (world/each-link-of b
          (lambda (L)
            (world/link-stiffness! L 0.55)
            (world/link-damping!   L 0.06)))))
    g))
```

## F.5 Chain

```scheme
;; A short heavy chain.
(define chain-links '())
(let loop ((i 0))
  (when (< i 8)
    (let ((b (world/spawn 'chain-link 240 (+ 40 (* i 20)))))
      (entity/mass! b 2.0)                ;; heavy
      (entity/drag! b 0.02)
      (when (= i 0) (entity/pin! b))
      (when (not (null? chain-links))
        (let ((L (world/link! (car chain-links) b)))
          (world/link-rest!      L 20)
          (world/link-stiffness! L 0.85)   ;; near-rigid
          (world/link-damping!   L 0.12)))
      (set! chain-links (cons b chain-links)))
    (loop (+ i 1))))
```

## F.6 Tearing

Add a stretch threshold: if the spring is stretched past 1.8x rest,
break it.

```scheme
;; After each frame, check for over-stretched links.
(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (world/each-link
      (lambda (L)
        (let* ((rest    (world/link-rest L))
               (current (world/link-current-length L))
               (stretch (/ current rest)))
          (when (> stretch 1.8)
            (world/link-remove! L)))))))
```

Cloth with a tearing threshold: pull hard on the mouse anchor and
the cloth rips where tension is highest. Great for fabric-damage
sims, for cardboard tearing, for skin (in a cartoon sense).

## F.7 Self-collision

Cloth normally doesn't self-collide; we treat threads as passing
through each other. For realistic cloth, add self-collision:

```scheme
(world/each 'thread
  (lambda (b)
    (ai/separate b 'thread 8 1.5)))
```

Each thread now weakly pushes other nearby threads. Enough to
prevent visible interpenetration; not enough to disrupt normal
draping. Costs O(n^2) per frame though — for 225 threads that's
50K checks. `world/spatial-index` helps.

## F.8 Air resistance

Add `entity/drag!` to each cloth ball. In still air, drag is small.
In wind, cloth billows:

```scheme
(world/wind! 0.5 0)   ;; sideways wind
(world/each 'thread
  (lambda (b) (entity/drag! b 0.03)))
```

Sideways wind + drag + top-pinned cloth = the flag effect. It ripples
and waves. If you also tune damping down slightly, the wave motion
persists.

## F.9 Adding shearing resistance

A grid of 4-neighbor springs allows the cloth to shear (deform into
parallelograms). To resist shearing, add diagonal springs:

```scheme
;; After building 4-neighbor springs, add diagonals.
(let loop-y ((r 0))
  (when (< r (- rows 1))
    (let loop-x ((c 0))
      (when (< c (- cols 1))
        (let ((L1 (world/link!
                    (vector-ref g (+ (* r cols) c))
                    (vector-ref g (+ (* (+ r 1) cols) c 1))))
              (L2 (world/link!
                    (vector-ref g (+ (* r cols) c 1))
                    (vector-ref g (+ (* (+ r 1) cols) c)))))
          (world/link-rest!      L1 (* spacing 1.414))
          (world/link-stiffness! L1 0.30)
          (world/link-damping!   L1 0.05)
          (world/link-rest!      L2 (* spacing 1.414))
          (world/link-stiffness! L2 0.30)
          (world/link-damping!   L2 0.05))
        (loop-x (+ c 1))))
    (loop-y (+ r 1))))
```

Diagonal springs at ~40% stiffness of the axis springs keep cloth
from shearing while still allowing normal draping.

## F.10 The takeaway

Stiffness controls springiness. Damping controls decay. Rest length
sets equilibrium. Everything else — rope, cloth, chain, hair,
jelly — is a triple of these values plus the topology of the links.
Print the tuning table; keep it in reach.

